net.akami.mask.handler.sign

Enum BinaryOperationSign

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<BinaryOperationSign>
      • net.akami.mask.handler.sign.BinaryOperationSign
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<BinaryOperationSign>

    public enum BinaryOperationSign
extends java.lang.Enum<BinaryOperationSign>
    A BinaryOperationSign links a char to a defined operation, taking two strings as inputs, and computing a single string out of the input. Binary operations also have a priority level, which determines whether an operation has a higher priority than another.

    For instance, the sum operator has a lower priority level than the mult operator, but an equal priority level to the subtract operator's.

    The operation is defined using method referencing, via the functional sub-interface BinaryOperationSign.BinaryMathCalculation. All referenced methods used belong to the MathUtils class created for this purpose.
    The None operator allows the user to deal with the different BinaryOperationSigns two by two, without getting any IndexOutOfBoundsException. See CalculationTree for more details about signs dealing and branch splitting. Note that the None operator might be removed in the future.
    See Also:
    for other operations

    • Enum Constant Detail

      • SUM

        public static final BinaryOperationSign SUM
        Sum operator, computes a + b using the MathUtils.sum(Expression, Expression) method.
        This operator can deal with a chain of additions / subtractions. Therefore, there will not be any problem if the a or b value happens to be a polynomial.
        Examples : 
         ---a---|---b---
    4   +   5     = 9
   4x   +   5     = 4x+5
  3+2x  +   x     = 3+3x
  3y-2  +   y     = 4y-2

      • SUBTRACT

        public static final BinaryOperationSign SUBTRACT
        Subtraction operator, computes a - b using the MathUtils.subtract(Expression, Expression) method.
        This operator works the same way as the SUM operator, except that it multiply all the monomials found in the b input by -1.
        Examples : 
         ---a---|---b---
    4   -   5     = -1
   4x   -   5     = 4x-5
  3+2x  -   x     = 3+x
  3y-2  -   y     = 2y-2

      • MULT

        public static final BinaryOperationSign MULT
        Mult operator, computes a * b using the MathUtils.mult(Expression, Expression) method.
        It also supports polynomial multiplication (not only the monomial ones) thus distributivity.
        Note that the unknown parts are always sorted alphabetically.
        Examples : 
         ---a---|---b---
    4   *   5     = 20
   4x   *   5     = 20x
  3+2x  *   x     = 3x+2x^2
  3y-2  *  x+y    = 3xy+3y^2-2x-2y

      • DIVIDE

        public static final BinaryOperationSign DIVIDE
        Division operator, computes a / b using the MathUtils.divide(Expression, Expression) method. Note that only the following division types are supported by now :
        • Numeric a and b
        • Monomial / Numeric a and b
        • Polynomial a and Monomial / Numeric b
        In other words, b can not be a polynomial, even if simplifications could technically be performed.
        Examples : 
         ---a---|---b---
    4   /   5     = 0.8
   4x   /   5     = 4x/5
  3+2x  /   x     = 3/x + 2
  3y-2  /  x+y    = Not calculable yet. Returns (3y-2)/(x+y)

      • POW

        public static final BinaryOperationSign POW
        Pow operator, computes a ^ b using the MathUtils.pow(Expression, Expression) method.
        The operator performs the calculation only if it is mathematically possible, therefore any monomial / polynomial to the power of a non integer number, as well as any algebraic exponent won't be calculated, thus the returned merge will be a^b, (a)^b, a^(b) or (a)^(b) depending of the case, so that the priority of operations is respected.
        The MaskContext also influences whether the calculation will be performed or not, if b is an integer. In fact, the context (or more precisely the CalculationCache) determines the maximal value of b before cancelling the operation.
        Examples : 
         ---a---|---b---
    4   ^   5     = 1024
  4x+y  ^   4     = 256x^4+256x^3y+96x^2y^2+16xy^3+y^4
  3+2x  ^   x     = (3+2x)^x
  3y-2  ^  x+y    = (3y-2)^(x+y)

      • NONE

        public static final BinaryOperationSign NONE
        The None operator does not have any other utility than making the amount of operations an even number. In other words, it allows the pow operator to have an other operation with an equal priority level.
        The purpose of this is to allow the CalculationTree to deal with operation signs two at once, without getting any IndexOutOfBoundsException.
        See Also:
        for further information
